  <title>-memvar</title>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1">-memvar</para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal">The -<text styleclass="Body Text">memvar</text> option tells the compiler to enable the support for &#160;&apos;memory variables&apos;. This option is also needed in the FoxPro dialect if you want to make local variables visible to the macro compiler with the <link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="opt-fox2">-fox2</link> compilation option.</para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Syntax</para>
    <para styleclass="Code with box">-memvar [+ | -] &#160;</para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Arguments</para>
    <para styleclass="List">+ | - <tab />Specifying +, or just -memvar, directs the compiler to enable support for memory variables.</para>
    <para styleclass="List"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Remarks</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">This will NOT work with the Core and Vulcan dialects.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Enabling this option will enable the following commands in the compiler:<br/></para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text">MEMVAR &lt;MemvarName,...&gt; </para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text">PUBLIC &lt;MemVarName,...&gt; &#160;</para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text">PRIVATE &lt;MemVarName,...&gt; </para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text">PARAMETERS &lt;ParameterName,,...&gt; </para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal" style="margin-left:13px;"><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="PropPage-Language">Click here to see the property page</link></para>
  </body>
